<h2>What PublicSchema provides</h2>
<p>
  PublicSchema is an open reference model for public service data.
  The <a href="/">homepage</a> covers the basics; this page goes deeper.
</p>
<p>It provides:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong><a href="/concepts/">Concepts</a></strong>: semantic entities (Person, Enrollment, Payment, and others) with definitions written for policy practitioners, not developers.</li>
  <li><strong><a href="/properties/">Properties</a></strong>: named, typed fields that apply to one or more concepts. Defined once and reused, keeping definitions consistent across domains.</li>
  <li><strong><a href="/vocab/">Vocabularies</a></strong>: controlled value sets. Where international standards exist (ISO, FHIR, UN), we reference them. Where they do not, we define a canonical set with mappings to how specific systems encode the same values.</li>
  <li><strong>Credential schemas</strong>: JSON-LD contexts and structures for issuing concept data as <a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/vc-data-model-2.0/">Verifiable Credentials</a>, using SD-JWT VC for selective disclosure of sensitive personal data.</li>
</ul>
<p>
  Every element gets a stable URI. Everything is optional. Countries and
  programs adopt what they need and extend what they don't.
</p>

